President of the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) Ahmad al-Fahad al-Sabah holds a placard announcing Doha as the host of the 21st Asian Games 2030 during the 39th OCA General Assembly Meeting in Oman's capital Muscat on December 16, 2020.
Photo credit: Haitham Al-Shukuraini | AFP


OCA President Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad Al-Sabah brokered a "win-win" solution which saw the city with the most votes earn the rights to host the 2030 Games and the second-placed bidder to organise the 2034 action, meaning that Riyadh will now host the latter.
Doha garnered 27 votes against Riyadh's 10 with eight abstentions at Muscat’s JW Marriott Hotel where 26 nations were present and 19 voted virtually.  It will be the second time for Qatar to host the Asian Games, the first time having been in 2006, while 2034 will be the first time for Riyadh to organise the championships.



