“The decision to grant the tournament to the Gulf peninsula has received almost universally negative press.
“Accusations of corruption in the 2010 vote abound, ranging from allegations that the Qatari state bribed relevant Fifa officials, to claims that lucrative oil and gas deals played a role in securing hosting rights for the Gulf peninsula.”
Doha has always denied these allegations and bravely fought to acquit themselves with the Gulf blockade also assisting them introspectively in developing self-reliance, especially in food security.





International Olympic Committee (IOC) President Thomas Bach delivers a speech on video during the 39th Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) General Assembly Meeting in the Omani capital Muscat on December 16, 2020 in which they will select host city for 2030 Asian Games.
Photo credit: Haitham Al-Shukuraini | AFP


At one point, Fifa President Gianni Infantino even mulled the idea of the Qatar World Cup expanding to 48 teams and increasing the number of host countries in an attempt to stifle the Gulf diplomatic tensions.
Infantino had hoped to see the extra matches hosted in Kuwait and Oman, but the idea was dropped as it was, ironically, seen as a fan to the Gulf tension flames.
Now, OCA’s win-win decision last week seems to have set the stage for better diplomatic and economic relations between Doha, Riyadh and the Gulf in general.



